      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And she looked and behold the king",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This, the literal translation of the Hebrew, is the form adopted in 2 Chron. The original is the same in both places.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "stood by a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "pillar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] By this word is clearly designated some spot which was the special position of the king on such occasions. We see that Athaliah took in the whole scene at a glance and knew without telling what was going on. The word ‘pillar’ is the same which is used for the two, Jachin and Boaz (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 7:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which stood as ornamental pillars in the porch of the temple, and which being ornamental could doubtless be seen by all in the court. If we suppose one of these set apart as the station of the king at his coronation, the position would be admirably suited for the purpose. Otherwise we must understand some special erection in the court of the temple, of which there is no mention till this passage, and afterwards in chap. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The situation of the pillar is described in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as ‘at the entering in’, words which would not unfitly describe the position of the two pillars erected in the temple porch.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as the manner",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was] Hence it was a well-known spot appropriated to such occasions.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and the princes and the trumpeters",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "the captains and the trumpets",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The ‘captains’ were those ‘over hundreds’ mentioned before. ‘Trumpets’ of course implies ‘trumpeters’ but the word is literally translated in 2 Chron., and the two places should agree. The persons who blew with the trumpets were probably the Levites, for in chap. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 12:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘trumpets’ are recounted as among the furniture of the temple, and these would be used only by priests or Levites. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 13:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we have the priests sounding trumpets.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and all the people of the land rejoiced",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Shewing that there was a numerous convocation. The gathering would be larger than usual because the Sabbath had been chosen for these operations.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Then",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Athaliah rent her clothes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Seeing with horror that priests and soldiery and the assembled people were all of one mind, and against her.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 14.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And when she looked, behold, the king stood by a pillar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "on the pillar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the raised platform",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The king's proper place in the temple seems to have been a raised standing-place (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "הָעַמּוּד",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עָמֹד",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to stand) in front of the entrance to the sanctuary, which made him very conspicuous (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and 2 Chron 34:31). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "As the manner was",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as was the usual practice when kings visited the temple - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and the princes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the centurions or captains of the guard - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and the trumpeters by the king",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - the officials whose business it was to blow the trumpet at a coronation (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 15:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and all the people of the land rejoiced, and blew with trumpets",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the people who had been admitted into the great court to witness the coronation. Some rumor of what was about to occur had got abroad, and many of the people had provided themselves with trumpets. As Dean Stanley puts it, \"The temple court was crowded with spectators, and they too took part in the celebration, and themselves prolonged the trumpet-blast, blended with the musical instruments of the temple service.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Athaliah rent her clothes.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Athaliah took in all with a single glance. She \"saw that the fatal hour was come\" (Stanley). With a strong hand she rent her royal robes, partly in horror, partly in despair; for the single glance which she had cast around was sufficient to show her that all was lost. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And cried, Treason! Treason!",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "conspiracy",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "conspiracy",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "! The cry was scarcely an appeal for help, as Josephus makes it ('Ant. Jud.,' 9:7. § 3), but rather an instinctive utterance, without distinct aim or object, wrung from her under the circumstances. It fell dead on the assembly. 2 Kings 11:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Death of Athaliah. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As soon as Athaliah heard the loud rejoicing of the people, she came to the people into the temple, and when she saw the youthful king in his standing-place surrounded by the princes, the trumpeters, and the whole of the people, rejoicing and blowing the trumpets, she rent her clothes with horror, and cried out, Conspiracy, conspiracy! העם הרצין does not mean the people running together, but the original reading in the text was probably והעם הרצין, the people and the halberdiers, and the Vav dropped out through an oversight of the copyist. By הרצין we are to understand the captains of the halberdiers with the armed Levites, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and העם is the people who had assembled besides (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In the Chronicles המּלך והמהללים הרצים is in apposition to העם: the noise of the people, the halberdiers, and those who praised the king. The עמּוּד, upon which the king stood, was not a pillar, but an elevated standing-place (suggestus) for the king at the eastern gate of the inner court (בּמּבוא,   ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " compared with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 46:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), when he visited the temple on festive occasions (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and it was most probably identical with the brazen scaffold (כּיּור) mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 6:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which would serve to explain כּמּשׁפּט, \"according to the right\" (Angl. V. \"as the manner was\"). השּׂרים are not merely the captains mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but these together with the rest of the assembled heads of the nation (האבות ראשׁי,   ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 13:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). החצצרות, the trumpets, the trumpeters. The reference is to the Levitical musicians mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 13:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 15:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; for they are distinguished from וגו כּל־העם, \"all the people of the land rejoicing and blowing the trumpets,\" i.e., not all the military men of the land who were present in Jerusalem (Thenius), but the mass of the people present in the temple (Bertheau).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]